Exploratory Data Analysis

After we have filtered our data for one channel, lets summarize all of the data. The table below gives us the sample size (N), mean (Mean), standard deviation (Std. Dev.), minimum (Min), 25th percentile (Pctl. 25), 75th percentile (Pctl. 75), and maximum (Max).


library(vtable)
st(df_train_x)

Next, lets learn more about our response variable: shares. Lets do a 5-number summary. It will show the minimum (Min.), first quartile (1st Qu.), median (Median), mean (Mean), third quartile (3rd Qu.), and maximum (Max.). This will help us get an idea about the overall spread of the shares data.

nrow(df_train_x)
[1] 1464
summary(df_train_x$shares)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
     28    1100    1700    3634    3200  208300

Next, lets plot a histogram of the shares data so that we can visually see it’s distribution. For example, we can determine if the distribution of shares is symmetric, skewed left, or skewed right.

df_train_x %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = shares)) + 
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(
    title = paste0("Histogram: Distribution of Shares for ", params$channel),
    y="Frequency",
    x="Shares")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Next, we’ll create a box plot. Before we do that, let’s make a binary version of the shares data. Using the mean of the shares data, we will give entries with a number of shares >= the mean a 1 and the rest a 0. This plot will show if the majority of shares is greater than or less than the mean of the shares. If it’s larger than the mean, the box plot over the 1 should be larger and more spread out than the one over the 0.

library(tidyverse)
binary <- function(S){
if(S>=mean(df_train_x$shares)){
A<-1
return(A)
}
if(S<mean(df_train_x$shares)){
A<-0
return(A)
}
}

boxplot_data_df_train_x <- df_train_x
boxplot_data_df_train_x$binary_shares <- as.numeric(sapply(df_train_x$shares, FUN=binary))
boxplot_data_df_train_x %>% select(binary_shares, shares, everything())

g <- ggplot(boxplot_data_df_train_x, aes(x = factor(binary_shares), y = shares))
  labs(x="Number of Shares (0: < mean of shares, 1: >= mean of shares)",
       y="Count")

Now, we will make a correlation plot comparing all of our numeric variables. When we do our modeling, we’re looking for correlations that are greater than 0.75 and less than -0.75. In the plot below, we are looking for the bright red and bright blue sections.

correlation_plot_df_train_x <- df_train_x

#correlation_plot_df_train_x <- correlation_plot_df_train_x %>% filter(channel==A) 

correlation_plot_df_train_x <- dplyr::select_if(correlation_plot_df_train_x, is.numeric)

r <- cor(correlation_plot_df_train_x, use="complete.obs")
library(ggplot2)
library(ggcorrplot)
ggcorrplot(r, 
            hc.order = TRUE, 
            type = "lower",
            tl.cex = 6,
           title = paste0("Correlation Plot for ",A))
